{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493065"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.09,0.13,0.74,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86828"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71100"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3339"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44265"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86828"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of sore throat and fever. His symptoms have not improved despite paracetamol, oral fluids and rest. He has previously been advised to seek medical attention if he develops persistent fever. He has a medical history of schizophrenia, hyperthyroidism, osteoarthritis and asthma. His medications include clozapine, carbimazole, perindopril, salbutamol and ibuprofen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears flushed. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important condition to exclude?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest infection","Thyrotoxicosis","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Agranulocytosis","Infectious mononucleosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is taking two medications (\u003Cstrong\u003Eagranulocytosis\u003C/strong\u003E-causing drugs - clozapine and carbimazole) that require regular monitoring due to the risk of bone marrow suppression. The presentation of fever and sore throat in this context requires urgent investigation with a full blood count to exclude this potentially life-threatening condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest infection\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the fever, but given the patient\u0027s medication history and specific instructions about fever, agranulocytosis must be excluded first. The absence of respiratory symptoms or signs makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyrotoxicosis\u003C/strong\u003E could cause fever and tachycardia, but the patient is already on carbimazole for hyperthyroidism, and other typical features such as tremor, anxiety, and weight loss are not described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a serious complication of antipsychotic medications characterised by hyperthermia, muscle rigidity, altered mental status, and autonomic dysfunction. While the patient is on clozapine, the presentation is not typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious mononucleosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects younger patients and presents with lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegular monitoring of white cell count is mandatory in patients taking clozapine or carbimazole. The risk of agranulocytosis is highest in the first six months of treatment and occurs more commonly in women, older patients, and those of Ashkenazi Jewish descent. If agranulocytosis is confirmed, both medications must be discontinued immediately.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clozapine and carbimazole can both cause agranulocytosis, requiring regular monitoring of white cell count","Fever in patients on these medications requires urgent investigation to exclude agranulocytosis","Agranulocytosis is more common in the first 6 months of treatment, in women, older patients and Ashkenazi Jews"],"references":["Side Effects of Psychotropic Medications. Jeff C. Huffman MD, Scott R. Beach MD and Theodore A. Stern MD. Massachusetts General Hospital Comprehensive Clinical Psychiatry, 51, 567-580.e4","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71100"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T20:05:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-24T20:06:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1212"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86828"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrin